Date: 0/0/1946
Source: Journal of the Polynesian Society
Author:
Vol / Page: 55/143
Edition:
Quote: ka[a]ka[a]po[o], a bird (Strigops habroptilus), ground-parrot; green parrot; night-parrot; once common in both islands, now confined to rugged south-west mountains of South Island (po, night, whence night-parrot).
Notes: Andersen Maori Words in English In O.E.D., but no macrons.

Date: 27/3/1897
Source: Star, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: The destruction of the bush, the introduction of stoats, weasels and ferrets, the increase of wild cats, the importation of European birds and the consequent greater demand made on the supply of bird-food, are all blamed, and no doubt those remarkable birds, the kakapo (or night parrot), the kiwi and the wood hen (weka) will fall an easy prey to stoats and weasels, more especially the two former, by reason of their sleeping in holes and hollow logs in the day time.
Notes:

